nd high-volume movements of capital in and out of those countries. Insufficient domestic controls and a sluggish international response further undermined these economies, as well as the credibility of external oversight agencies like the International Monetary Fund. This timely volume examines the correlation between volatile capital mobility, currency instability, and the threat of regional contagion, focusing particular attention on the emergent economies of Latin America, Southeast Asia, and Eastern Europe. Together these studies offer a new understanding of the empirical relationship between capital flows, international trade, and economic performance, and also afford key insights into realms of major policy concern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCapital movements -- Developing countries -- Congresses. 0aCapital movementszDeveloping countriesvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  acapital flows, economy, economics, international, management, foreign investments, speculative, speculation, movements of money, finances, wealth, regional contagion, currency instability, currencies, volatile mobility, latin america, southeast asia, eastern europe, trade, performance, developing countries, globalization, emerging markets, liberalization, debt, exchange rates, former soviet union, russia, mexico, thailand, south korea, brazil.1 aBacchetta, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBekaert, Geert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalvo, Guillermo A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaessens, Stijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Gregorio, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDooley, Michael P., econtributor.4c